Forecasting

Store-233779 for Soups-Campbells

Aligining with the business objective of inventory management for the next month, forecasting goal is to predict the number of units to be sold in next four weeks i.e Week= 53, 54, 55 and 56. From the main data set soup we aggregated the units on weekly basis for store-233779(basis of IRI_Key). This time series is then used through out this analysis.

Looking at the following time series plot of this data, we can say that it has level, trend might or might not be present, which will be cleared later in this analysis and seasonality is not present. Also from ACF plot it is clear that series is not autcorelatead.

library(forecast)


soups <- read.csv("Campbells_233779_data.csv")
soupstimeseries <- ts(soups)

# findfrequency(soupstimeseries)

ggtsdisplay(soupstimeseries)

Since this series contains data for 52 weeks hence cycle can not be detected, following plot gives better insight on seasonality.

monthplot(soupstimeseries)

From above plot it is clear there is no seasonality in this series.

Before proceeding to fit different models on this series, we forecasted on basis of naive and mean method.

soupfit1 <- meanf(soupstimeseries, h = 4)
soupfit2 <- naive(soupstimeseries, h = 4)


plot(soupfit1, plot.conf = FALSE, main = "Forecasts for quarterly beer production")
lines(soupfit2$mean, col = 2)

lines(soupstimeseries)
legend("topright", lty = 1, col = c(1, 2), legend = c("Mean method", "Naive method"))

Following are the results of accuracy for these two methods.

print("Accuracy of mean method")
## [1] "Accuracy of mean method"
accuracy(soupfit1)
##              ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE      MASE      ACF1

print("Accuracy of naive method")
## [1] "Accuracy of naive method"
accuracy(soupfit2)
##                    ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE MASE       ACF1
## Training set 1.823529 270.6552 153.7059 -13.66429 42.98812    1 -0.4543271
res1 <- residuals(soupfit1)
plotForecastErrors(res1)

As trend is not clearly visible in this time series, we will fit different models and on basis of accuracy measures and residual analysis we will decide the best model to forecast.

Before running the model we have partitioned the series in training set with first 48 weeks and remaining weeks are kept in validation set as our forecast horizon is four weeks.

souptraining <- ts(soupstimeseries[c(1:48), ])
soupvalidation <- ts(soupstimeseries[c(49:52), ])

Starting with regression models:

  1. Linear Regression Model
soup.fit3 <- tslm(souptraining ~ trend)
f3 <- forecast(soup.fit3, h = 4, level = c(80, 95))
plot(f3, ylab = "Units sold per week", xlab = "Week", main = "Forecast from Linear Model")
lines(fitted(soup.fit3), col = "blue")

accuracy(f3)
##                         ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE      MASE
## Training set -7.696534e-15 214.1297 141.6938 -33.54429 58.92074 0.9286862
##                   ACF1
## Training set 0.2052765

This model gave us RMSE of 214.12 and MAPE 58.92%, we further analyse the residuals of this model.

res3 <- residuals(soup.fit3)
# plot(res3, main='Residuals from linear regression method',
# ylab='residuals', xlab='Week') abline(0,0,col='gray60')
Acf(res3, main = "ACF of linear regression residuals")

plotForecastErrors(res3, "Histograms of Linear Model Residuals")

From ACF plot it is visible that there is no autocorelation but from residuals histogram we can see that mean of residuals are somewhat close to zero and residuals are not normally distributed. However we can not conclude this as the best model to forecats without running other models.

  1. Quadratic Regression Model
soup.fit4 <- tslm(souptraining ~ trend + I(trend^2))
f4 <- forecast(soup.fit4, h = 4, level = c(80, 95))
plot(f4, ylab = "Units sold per week", xlab = "Week", main = "Forecast from Quadratic Model")
lines(fitted(soup.fit4), col = "blue")

accuracy(f4)
##                        ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE      MASE
## Training set 4.143532e-15 200.7228 119.5233 -23.74664 42.82662 0.7833769
##                    ACF1
## Training set 0.09213691

Looking from actual vs predicted plot we can say that this model is fitting our series in a much better way. Also it gave us RMSE of 200.72 and MAPE 42.82% which is much better than former linear model , we further analyse the residuals of this model.

res4 <- residuals(soup.fit4)
# plot(res4, main='Residuals from Quadratic Model', ylab='residuals',
# xlab='Week') abline(0,0,col='gray60')
Acf(res4, main = "ACF of Quadratic Model residuals")

plotForecastErrors(res4, "Histograms of Quadratic Model Residuals")

There is no autocorelation in residuals, also from histogram it is visible that residuals are normally distributed around the mean zero.

As we found that quadrtic model performed better, we tried to smoothened the series to get some clear picture about trend. We performed centered moving average and weigthed moving average smoothing and got following graphs.

plot(soupstimeseries, main = "Smoothing-Center Moving Average", ylab = "units#", 
    xlab = "Week")
lines(ma(soupstimeseries, 8), col = "red")

plot(soupstimeseries, main = "Smoothing-Weighted Moving Average", ylab = "units#", 
    xlab = "Week")
lines(ma(ma(soupstimeseries, 4), 2), col = "red")

From both the graphs we can say that somewhat quadtratic trend is present in series (in red).

Before concluding quadtratic model as best for our series we tried running few data driven model as well.

It is clear from above results that quadtratic regression model fits best to this series with least RMSE of 121.1 and 35.4% of MAPE. Hence we forecasted next four weeks units to be sold by using quadtratic regression model as follows.

soup.fitfinal <- tslm(soupstimeseries ~ trend + I(trend^2))
ffinal <- forecast(soup.fitfinal, h = 4, level = c(80, 95))
plot(ffinal, ylab = "Units sold per week", xlab = "Week", main = "Forecast from Quadratic Model")
lines(fitted(soup.fitfinal), col = "blue")

print("Forecasted Values")
